<BaseLayout
  title="Tsarevna — Case Study - Anastasia Bessonova"
  description="Full case study: narrative design for Tsarevna, a dark fantasy action game by Watt Studio. Research, approach, and deliverables."
>
  <section class="block reading flow">
    <h1>Case study: Tsarevna</h1>
    <p class="muted">
      Dark Fantasy Action Game · Watt Studio · PC (Steam) · Released 2026
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section block reading flow">
    <h2>Context</h2>
    <p>
      Tsarevna is a dark fantasy action game developed at Watt Studio, where players embody
      a powerful princess navigating a treacherous, myth-inspired world.
    </p>
    <p>
      My role was Narrative Designer and Screenwriter, responsible for lore development,
      character design and backstories, quest design, and integrating narrative with game design.
      I worked in close collaboration with game designers and artists throughout production.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section block reading flow">
    <h2>Narrative problem</h2>
    <p>
      The project required establishing a strong, immediate emotional connection between the
      player and a female protagonist in a genre often dominated by stereotypical characters.
      The narrative needed to provide depth and motivation while supporting fast-paced gameplay —
      without slowing it down or feeling disconnected from the action.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Create a protagonist players connect with immediately and emotionally</li>
      <li>Avoid genre stereotypes while meeting dark fantasy expectations</li>
      <li>Ensure narrative supports — not interrupts — fast-paced gameplay</li>
      <li>Build lore that feels cohesive and discoverable, not front-loaded</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="section block reading flow">
    <h2>Constraints</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Aligning with existing dark fantasy art direction and visual identity</li>
      <li>Integrating lore seamlessly into an action-oriented experience</li>
      <li>Supporting core gameplay loops without narrative interruption</li>
      <li>Iterative production with evolving design decisions</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="section block reading flow">
    <h2>Approach</h2>
    <p>
      I began with targeted research into evolving trends and player reception of female
      characters in action games — looking at what resonated, what felt hollow, and why.
    </p>
    <p>
      Based on those findings, I proposed and developed a <strong>dual-character dynamic</strong>:
      the Princess and her companion/reflection. Rather than relying on a single archetype to
      carry all emotional weight, this structure created layered narrative tension through the
      relationship between the two characters — their conflict, alignment, and evolution together.
    </p>
    <p>
      This approach allowed the emotional core of the story to emerge through interaction
      rather than exposition, keeping it compatible with the game's action pacing. Lore was
      distributed across discoverable elements rather than delivered upfront.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section block reading flow">
    <h2>Deliverables</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Lore documents and world-building framework</li>
      <li>Character backstories and relationship arcs</li>
      <li>Quest narratives integrated into the game's design</li>
      <li>Narrative documentation for cross-team alignment</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="section block reading flow">
    <h2>Outcome</h2>
    <p>
      The narrative foundation and character dynamic were successfully integrated into the
      released version. Player discussions and early feedback specifically highlight the
      protagonists' relationship and the world's lore as compelling strengths of the project.
    </p>
